[[Ana Maria Groza]]|ROM}}||'''1:31:35''' ||\n|-\n| 12 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[In\u00eas Henriques]]|POR}}||'''1:31:58''' ||\n|-\n| 13 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Zuzana Mal\u00edkov\u00e1]]|SVK}}||'''1:32:14''' || [[Slovakian records in athletics|NR]]\n|-\n| 14 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Susana Feitor]]|POR}}||'''1:32:19''' ||\n|-\n| 15 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Mar\u00eda Vasco]]|ESP}}||'''1:32:50''' || [[File:Sport records icon SB.svg|22px|Season Best]]\n|-\n| 16 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Gisella Orsini]]|ITA}}||'''1:33:10''' || [[File:Sport records icon SB.svg|22px|Season Best]]\n|-\n| 17 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Galina Kolpakova]]|RUS}}||''' 1:33:39 ||\n|-\n| 18 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Rossella Giordano]]|ITA}}||''' 1:33:56 ||\n|-\n| 19 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Poves]]|ESP}}||''' 1:35:03 ||\n|-\n| 20 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Beatriz Pascual]]|ESP}}||''' 1:36:03 ||\n|-\n| 21 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Sonata Milu\u0161auskait\u0117]]|LTU}}||'''1:36:20''' ||\n|-\n| 22 ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Monica Svensson]]|SWE}}||'''1:38:25''' ||\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|DID NOT FINISH (DNF)\n|-\n| &mdash; ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Kristina Saltanovi\u010d]]|LTU}}||'''DNF'''\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|DISQUALIFIED (DSQ)\n|-\n| &mdash; ||align=left| {{flagathlete|[[Elena Ginko]]|BLR}}||'''DSQ'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2006 Race Walking Year Ranking]]\n\n==References==\n* [http://www.tilastopaja.org/staticresults/eaa9235808.htm Official results]\n* [http://todor66.com/athletics/europe/2006/Women_20km_Walk.html Results]\n<br />\n{{EC20kmwalk}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2006 European Athletics Championships - Women's 20 kilometres walk}}\n[[Category:Events at the 2006 European Athletics Championships|Walk 20 km]]\n[[Category:Racewalking at the European Athletics Championships]]\n[[Category:2006 in women's athletics]]\n\n\n{{Athletics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_European_Athletics_Championships_%E2%80%93_Women%27s_20_kilometres_walk"}
{"title_page": "Takeshi Motomiya", "text_new": "{{use dmy|date=April 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Weasel|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{short description|Japanese artist}}\n{{Japanese name|Takeshi}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| native_name        = \u672c\u5bae\u5065\u53f2\n| native_name_lang   = jp\n| image              = Takeshi Motomiya at Encant.png\n| caption            = Motomiya at Encant 2012-11\n| birth_name         = Motomiya Takeshi\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1959|12|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shibuya]], Tokyo, Japan\n| residence          = [[Barcelona]], Catalonia, Spain\n| nationality        = Japanese\n| education          = [[Tama Art University]], Tokyo, Japan\n| occupation         = Professional artist\n| years_active       = 1984\u2013present\n| known_for          = Painting, [[Engraving]]\n| style              = [[Abstract Art]]\n| relatives          = {{unbulleted list\n  | ''[[Migishi Setsuko]]'' (Grandmother)\n  | ''Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d'' (Grandfather)}}\n| website            ={{url|takeshimotomiya.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Takeshi Motomiya''' ({{CJKV|j=\u672c\u5bae \u5065\u53f2}} ''Motomiya Takeshi'' ({{IPA-ja|motom\u02b2ija take\u0255i}}), born 5 December 1959, Tokyo, Japan) is a multidisciplinary Japanese artist living in [[Barcelona]] since 1986.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://encant.net/artista/takeshi-motomiya|title=Takeshi Motomiya \u2013 Encant|website=encant.net|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> Throughout his career, he has worked within various visual arts disciplines that include painting, [[engraving]], and sculpture. Characterized by his work of textures and natural pigment colors, his work is mainly based on [[abstract art]] and shows some attributes of figurativism and [[abstract expressionism]], infused with [[Japanese mythology|ancient Japanese gods]], [[Bible|biblical content]], and [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Egyptian mythology|Egyptian]] mythology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yamaguchi-gallery.com/\u753b\u5eca\u901a\u4fe1-vol-164/|title=\u753b\u5eca\u901a\u4fe1 Vol.164|last=\u5c71\u53e3|first=\u96c4\u4e00\u90ce|date=March 17, 2017|website=\u5c71\u53e3\u753b\u5eca|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRaised and trained in Japan, and having lived in Paris before settling in Barcelona, Motomiya's work has been exhibited in several European cities such as Barcelona, Paris, [[Amsterdam]] and Mah\u00f3n (Minorca). However the vast majority of his works are exhibited in his native country, Japan.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.takeshimotomiya.com/the-artist.html|title=The Artist|website=takeshimotomiya.com|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThrough his specialization in engraving and the subsequent creation of the Taller Nou studio, he has worked with national and international artists, such as [[Antoni T\u00e0pies]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Antoni T\u00e0pies in print|last=Wye|first=Deborah|publisher=MoMA (The Museum of Modern Art)|year=1991|isbn=0870706020|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/antonitapiesinpr0000wyed/page/7 7,117,118]|url=https://archive.org/details/antonitapiesinpr0000wyed/page/7}}</ref> Barry Flanagan, [[Balthus]], [[Miquel Barcel\u00f3]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sol Y Sombra, Miquel Barcel\u00f3|last=|first=|publisher=Actes Sud / Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France / Mus\u00e9e national Picasso-Paris|year=2016|isbn=9782330060329|location=Paris, France|pages=218}}</ref> and [[Perejaume]]. The studio has been acknowledged as one of the best printmaking studios in Spain.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2006/12/07/quaderncat/1165455923_850215.html|title=Icones i s\u00edmbols|last=Casamartina i Parassols|first=Josep|date=December 7, 2006|work=El Pa\u00eds (Newspaper)|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTakeshi Motomiya was born on 5 December 1959 in [[Shibuya|Shibuya, Tokyo]]. He was born into a highborn family of painters, and grew up surrounded by an artistic environment, between galleries and exhibitions. His grandmother, [[Migishi Setsuko]] ({{CJKV|j=\u4e09\u5cb8 \u7bc0\u5b50}}, 1905\u20131999),<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yamaguchi-gallery.com/artists/|title=Yamaguchi Gallery \u2013 Artists|last=\u5c71\u53e3|first=\u96c4\u4e00\u90ce|date=17 March 2010|website=\u5c71\u53e3\u753b\u5eca|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 January 2019}}</ref> known as one of the pioneering Japanese women in oil painting,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s-migishi.com/information.html|title=Ichinomiya City Memorial Art Museum of Setsuko Migishi|date=|website=Migishi Setsuko Official Site|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref> and his grandfather, {{ill|Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d|ja|\u4e09\u5cb8 \u597d\u592a\u90ce|de|Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d||lt=|WD=}} ({{CKJV|j=\u4e09\u5cb8 \u597d\u592a\u90ce}}, 1903\u20131934), known as one of the first painters who began paintings by surrealism in Japan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dokyoi.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/hk/mkb/english.htm|title=Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d Museum of Art|date=|website=Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d Museum's Website|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 January 2019}}</ref> were the main influential characters in Motomiya's interest towards the art world.{{whom|date=April 2020}}\n\nHe graduated in Fine Arts in 1982, with a master's degree specializing in engraving techniques in 1984 by the [[Tama Art University|Tama Art University of Tokyo]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite the fact that his academic background was focused on engraving, his personal development as an artist has matured above all in the area of painting.{{whom|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1984, with an invitation from his grandmother who at the time was living in France, Motomiya undertook his first trip to Europe with the intention of getting to know the art of European museums. While residing in France, Motomiya travelled around Europe were he had the opportunity to exhibit alongside his grandparents, and his uncle in a joint exhibition at the Galerie d\u2019Eendt in Amsterdam in 1986.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt was that same year, in one of his European trips where Motomiya, at the age of 27, fell in love with the city of Barcelona, where he has been established since 1986. It was upon his settlement in Barcelona that Motomiya began to focus entirely on his painting.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Career ==\nMotomiya's work has been exhibited mainly in art galleries in Tokyo such as the Ueda Gallery, the Galerie 421, the 21+yo, the Okumura Gallery or the Libre Gallery. He has shown his work in art galleries across Japan as well; at the Yamaguchi Gallery in Chiba, and the Ecru-no-mori Gallery in Mishima. He has participated in several editions of the Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair, currently known as Art Fair Tokyo, and has exhibited at various editions of the Japan Art Dealers Association in Tokyo.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOutside Japan, Motomiya's work has been mostly exhibited in Europe, in cities such as Barcelona, Paris, Amsterdam and Mah\u00f3n (Minorca) where he has been regularly exhibiting since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encant.net/artista/takeshi-motomiya?lang=es|title=Takeshi Motomiya's Exhibitions at Encant|date=|website=Encant Gallery|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>{{Quote box\n| quote = \"On my first meeting with Takeshi Motomiya, I instantly recognized, seeing his paintings and he, himself, before me, that he was the figure who appeared in them. [...] he is none other than an \u201cartist painted by pictures.\u201d He himself emerges out of the paintings he creates; there is no need for him to step out of the frame and proclaim his creed or explain the rationale behind his work. What people see when they look at his paintings is Takeshi Motomiya himself. It is enough for people to distinctly feel how this silent, reserved figure seems to be speaking loud and clear in the paintings.\"\n| source = \u2013 Makoto \u014coka, in ''Poets and Artists''<ref name=\":2\"/>\n| width = 30%\n| border = 0px\n| salign = right\n}}During his first exhibition at the 5th NiCAF in 1997, Motomiya was introduced to the Japanese poet and literary critic, [[Makoto \u014coka]] (\u5927\u5ca1 \u4fe1, 1931\u20132017). After seeing Motomiya's work, \u014coka described him as the ''artist painted by pictures,'' which he later used as the title for the article in which he wrote about Motomiya's work.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.library.metro.tokyo.jp/winj/opac/switch-detail-iccap.do?bibid=1152293817|title=\u8a69\u4eba\u3068\u7f8e\u8853\u5bb6 \u2013 \u30b7\u30b8\u30f3 \u30c8 \u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30c4\u30ab|last=\u5927\u5ca1|first=\u4fe1|publisher=\u5927\u5ca1\u4fe1\u30d5\u30a9\u30fc\u30e9\u30e0,\u82b1\u795e\u793e(\u767a\u58f2)|year=2013|isbn=978-4-7602-1996-4|location=\u4e09\u5cf6,\u6771\u4eac|pages=187\u2013190|author-link=Makoto \u014coka}}</ref> \u014coka who came to admire the artist's work, became a regular buyer of Motomiya's work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ezoushi.com/ooka_collection/01.html|title=Poet's Eyes - Makoto \u014coka's Collection Exhibition|date=|website=Ezoushi|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Today, some of those paintings are part of the private collection exhibited at the [[:ja:\u5927\u5ca1\u4fe1\u3053\u3068\u3070\u9928|\u014coka Makoto Kotoba Museum]], in [[Mishima, Shizuoka|Mishima, Shizuoka Prefecture]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mitaka.jpn.org/calender/gallery/067.php|title=Makoto \u014coka Collection Exhibition|date=|publisher=Mitaka City Arts Foundation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Motomiya began teaching printmaking techniques at the Escola Massana of Barcelona within the ''Experimental Edition Course'' of the Massana Permanent program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://robertabridda.com/?page_id=227|title=Experimental Edition Course at Massana Permanent|last=Bridda|first=Roberta|date=|website=Workshops \u2013 Massana Permanent|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> The course was taught until 2012.\n\n=== Taller Nou studio ===\nAfter settling in Barcelona, in 1989, while continuing his work in painting, he and an associate founded the Taller Nou studio, which became a printmaking studio specialized in engraving and etching techniques for professional artists.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSince the beginning of their work as printmakers, and for more than twenty years, they were the only printmaking studio of Antoni T\u00e0pies' work.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In fact, they kept working with him until the artist's passing in 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.menorca.info/menorca/migracion/2010/02/09/514374/percepcion-desde-sentidos.html|title=Takeshi Motomiya comparte su mundo interior en Encant. Una oda de equilibrio por la esperanza.|last=Marqu\u00e9s|first=Raquel|date=February 9, 2010|work=Menorca (Newspaper)|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://botiga.fundaciotapies.org/graphic-works/vuit-i-tres-ics-2004-with-wide-margins|title=\"Vuit i tres ics\", 2004|date=|website=Antoni T\u00e0pies Foundation \u2013 Online Shop|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref> Apart from T\u00e0pies, they have worked with many other national and international artists, among which are Barry Flanagan, [[Balthus]], [[Miquel Barcel\u00f3]] and [[Perejaume]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOriginally located in the Gracia district of Barcelona, the studio has been acknowledged{{by who|date=April 2020}} as one of the best printmaking studios in Spain.<ref name=\":1\" /> Their work has been exhibited in museums around the world such as the [[Museum of Modern Art|Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)]] of New York,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/exhibitions/366|title=Antoni T\u00e0pies in Print at The Museum of Modern Art|date=May 7, 1992|website=The Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> during the ''Antoni T\u00e0pies in Print'' exhibition,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moma.org/documents/moma_press-release_327627.pdf|title=Antoni T\u00e0pies in Print Press Release|date=July 1991|access-date=January 10, 2019|publisher=MoMA (Press Release)}}</ref> or at the [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso|Mus\u00e9e Picasso Paris]], during ''Miquel Barcel\u00f3, Sol y Sombra'' exhibit in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museepicassoparis.fr/miquel-barcelo-sol-y-sombra/|title=Sol y Sombra, Miquel Barcel\u00f3 at Mus\u00e9e Picasso Paris|date=|website=Mus\u00e9e Picasso Paris|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nSelected solo and group exhibitions;<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.takeshimotomiya.com/past-exhibitions.html|title=Past Exhibitions|website=takeshimotomiya.com|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* 1989 \u2013 Group exhibition at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain).\n* 1990 \u2013 Group exhibitions at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain), FIAC SAGA '90 (Paris, France) and Central Gallery (Sabadell, Spain).\n* 1991 \u2013 Group exhibition at Central Gallery (Sabadell, Spain).\n* 1992 \u2013 Group exhibition at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain).\n* 1993 \u2013 Group exhibition at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain).\n* 1996 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Artara Gallery (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 1997 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at the 5th NiCAF* (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair)(Tokyo, Japan) and Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 1998 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 1999 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan) and the 6th NiCAF* (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair)(Tokyo, Japan). Group exhibition at JADA (Japan Art Dealers Association)(Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2000 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan) and group exhibition at JADA (Japan Art Dealers Association)(Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2001 \u2013 Solo exhibition at the 7th NiCAF* (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair)(Tokyo, Japan) and group exhibition at JADA (Japan Art Dealers Association)(Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2002 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain).\n* 2003 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2004 \u2013 Group exhibition at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain).\n* 2005 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Gallery 21 + Yo (Tokyo, Japan) and group exhibitions at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain) and Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2006 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain) and Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan). Group exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2008 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Okumura Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2009 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain) and group exhibition at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain).\n* 2010 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan) and group exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2011 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Galerie 421 (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2012 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Gallery Ecru-no-mori (Mishima, Japan) and Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain)\n* 2013 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan).\n* 2014 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Libre Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2016 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Galerie Couteron (Paris, France).\n* 2017 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan), Libre Gallery (Tokyo, Japan) and Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n\n<small>*NICAF (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair) \u2013 Currently known as Art Fair Tokyo.</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.takeshimotomiya.com Official Site]\n*[https://www.yamaguchi-gallery.com/artists/ Yamaguchi Gallery \u2013 Artist Profiles]\n*[http://www.galerie-couteron.com/artiste-takeshi_motomiya Galerie Couteron \u2013 Takeshi Motomiya] \n*[http://www.inks-passagedencres.fr/spip.php?article679 Takeshi Motomiya: M\u00e9diter, par Martine Monteau]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Motomiya, Takeshi}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese painters]]\n[[Category:Japanese contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from Shibuya]]\n[[Category:Tama Art University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy|date=April 2020}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Weasel|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{short description|Japanese artist}}\n{{Japanese name|Takeshi}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = \n| native_name        = \u672c\u5bae\u5065\u53f2\n| native_name_lang   = jp\n| image              = Takeshi Motomiya at Encant.png\n| caption            = Motomiya at Encant 2012-11\n| birth_name         = Motomiya Takeshi\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1959|12|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shibuya]], Tokyo, Japan\n| residence          = [[Barcelona]], Catalonia, Spain\n| nationality        = Japanese\n| education          = [[Tama Art University]], Tokyo, Japan\n| occupation         = Professional artist\n| years_active       = 1984\u2013present\n| known_for          = Painting, [[Engraving]]\n| style              = [[Abstract Art]]\n| relatives          = {{unbulleted list\n  | ''[[Migishi Setsuko]]'' (Grandmother)\n  | ''Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d'' (Grandfather)}}\n| website            ={{url|takeshimotomiya.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Takeshi Motomiya''' ({{CJKV|j=\u672c\u5bae \u5065\u53f2}} ''Motomiya Takeshi'' ({{IPA-ja|motom\u02b2ija take\u0255i}}), born 5 December 1959, Tokyo, Japan) is a multidisciplinary Japanese artist living in [[Barcelona]] since 1986.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://encant.net/artista/takeshi-motomiya|title=Takeshi Motomiya \u2013 Encant|website=encant.net|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> Throughout his career, he has worked within various visual arts disciplines that include painting, [[engraving]], and sculpture. Characterized by his work of textures and natural pigment colors, his work is mainly based on [[abstract art]] and shows some attributes of figurativism and [[abstract expressionism]], infused with [[Japanese mythology|ancient Japanese gods]], [[Bible|biblical content]], and [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Egyptian mythology|Egyptian]] mythology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yamaguchi-gallery.com/\u753b\u5eca\u901a\u4fe1-vol-164/|title=\u753b\u5eca\u901a\u4fe1 Vol.164|last=\u5c71\u53e3|first=\u96c4\u4e00\u90ce|date=March 17, 2017|website=\u5c71\u53e3\u753b\u5eca|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRaised and trained in Japan, and having lived in Paris before settling in Barcelona, Motomiya's work has been exhibited in several European cities such as Barcelona, Paris, [[Amsterdam]] and Mah\u00f3n (Minorca). However the vast majority of his works are exhibited in his native country, Japan.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.takeshimotomiya.com/the-artist.html|title=The Artist|website=takeshimotomiya.com|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThrough his specialization in engraving and the subsequent creation of the Taller Nou studio, he has worked with national and international artists, such as [[Antoni T\u00e0pies]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=Antoni T\u00e0pies in print|last=Wye|first=Deborah|publisher=MoMA (The Museum of Modern Art)|year=1991|isbn=0870706020|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/antonitapiesinpr0000wyed/page/7 7,117,118]|url=https://archive.org/details/antonitapiesinpr0000wyed/page/7}}</ref> Barry Flanagan, [[Balthus]], [[Miquel Barcel\u00f3]]<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sol Y Sombra, Miquel Barcel\u00f3|last=|first=|publisher=Actes Sud / Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France / Mus\u00e9e national Picasso-Paris|year=2016|isbn=9782330060329|location=Paris, France|pages=218}}</ref> and [[Perejaume]]. The studio has been acknowledged as one of the best printmaking studios in Spain.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2006/12/07/quaderncat/1165455923_850215.html|title=Icones i s\u00edmbols|last=Casamartina i Parassols|first=Josep|date=December 7, 2006|work=El Pa\u00eds (Newspaper)|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nTakeshi Motomiya was born on December 5, 1959 in [[Shibuya|Shibuya, Tokyo]]. He was born into a highborn family of painters, and grew up surrounded by an artistic environment, between galleries and exhibitions. His grandmother, [[Migishi Setsuko]] ({{CJKV|j=\u4e09\u5cb8 \u7bc0\u5b50}}, 1905\u20131999),<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yamaguchi-gallery.com/artists/|title=Yamaguchi Gallery \u2013 Artists|last=\u5c71\u53e3|first=\u96c4\u4e00\u90ce|date=March 17, 2010|website=\u5c71\u53e3\u753b\u5eca|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> known as one of the pioneering Japanese women in oil painting,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s-migishi.com/information.html|title=Ichinomiya City Memorial Art Museum of Setsuko Migishi|date=|website=Migishi Setsuko Official Site|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> and his grandfather, {{ill|Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d|ja|\u4e09\u5cb8 \u597d\u592a\u90ce|de|Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d||lt=|WD=}} ({{CKJV|j=\u4e09\u5cb8 \u597d\u592a\u90ce}}, 1903\u20131934), known as one of the first painters who began paintings by surrealism in Japan,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dokyoi.pref.hokkaido.lg.jp/hk/mkb/english.htm|title=Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d Museum of Art|date=|website=Migishi K\u014dtar\u014d Museum's Website|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> were the main influential characters in Motomiya's interest towards the art world.{{whom|date=April 2020}}\n\nHe graduated in Fine Arts in 1982, with a master's degree specializing in engraving techniques in 1984 by the [[Tama Art University|Tama Art University of Tokyo]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Despite the fact that his academic background was focused on engraving, his personal development as an artist has matured above all in the area of painting.{{whom|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1984, with an invitation from his grandmother who at the time was living in France, Motomiya undertook his first trip to Europe with the intention of getting to know the art of European museums. While residing in France, Motomiya travelled around Europe were he had the opportunity to exhibit alongside his grandparents, and his uncle in a joint exhibition at the Galerie d\u2019Eendt in Amsterdam in 1986.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt was that same year, in one of his European trips where Motomiya, at the age of 27, fell in love with the city of Barcelona, where he has been established since 1986. It was upon his settlement in Barcelona that Motomiya began to focus entirely on his painting.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Career ==\nMotomiya's work has been exhibited mainly in art galleries in Tokyo such as the Ueda Gallery, the Galerie 421, the 21+yo, the Okumura Gallery or the Libre Gallery. He has shown his work in art galleries across Japan as well; at the Yamaguchi Gallery in Chiba, and the Ecru-no-mori Gallery in Mishima. He has participated in several editions of the Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair, currently known as Art Fair Tokyo, and has exhibited at various editions of the Japan Art Dealers Association in Tokyo.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nOutside Japan, Motomiya's work has been mostly exhibited in Europe, in cities such as Barcelona, Paris, Amsterdam and Mah\u00f3n (Minorca) where he has been regularly exhibiting since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encant.net/artista/takeshi-motomiya?lang=es|title=Takeshi Motomiya's Exhibitions at Encant|date=|website=Encant Gallery|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>{{Quote box\n| quote = \"On my first meeting with Takeshi Motomiya, I instantly recognized, seeing his paintings and he, himself, before me, that he was the figure who appeared in them. [...] he is none other than an \u201cartist painted by pictures.\u201d He himself emerges out of the paintings he creates; there is no need for him to step out of the frame and proclaim his creed or explain the rationale behind his work. What people see when they look at his paintings is Takeshi Motomiya himself. It is enough for people to distinctly feel how this silent, reserved figure seems to be speaking loud and clear in the paintings.\"\n| source = \u2013 Makoto \u014coka, in ''Poets and Artists''<ref name=\":2\"/>\n| width = 30%\n| border = 0px\n| salign = right\n}}During his first exhibition at the 5th NiCAF in 1997, Motomiya was introduced to the Japanese poet and literary critic, [[Makoto \u014coka]] (\u5927\u5ca1 \u4fe1, 1931\u20132017). After seeing Motomiya's work, \u014coka described him as the ''artist painted by pictures,'' which he later used as the title for the article in which he wrote about Motomiya's work.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|url=https://catalog.library.metro.tokyo.jp/winj/opac/switch-detail-iccap.do?bibid=1152293817|title=\u8a69\u4eba\u3068\u7f8e\u8853\u5bb6 \u2013 \u30b7\u30b8\u30f3 \u30c8 \u30d3\u30b8\u30e5\u30c4\u30ab|last=\u5927\u5ca1|first=\u4fe1|publisher=\u5927\u5ca1\u4fe1\u30d5\u30a9\u30fc\u30e9\u30e0,\u82b1\u795e\u793e(\u767a\u58f2)|year=2013|isbn=978-4-7602-1996-4|location=\u4e09\u5cf6,\u6771\u4eac|pages=187\u2013190|author-link=Makoto \u014coka}}</ref> \u014coka who came to admire the artist's work, became a regular buyer of Motomiya's work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ezoushi.com/ooka_collection/01.html|title=Poet's Eyes - Makoto \u014coka's Collection Exhibition|date=|website=Ezoushi|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Today, some of those paintings are part of the private collection exhibited at the [[:ja:\u5927\u5ca1\u4fe1\u3053\u3068\u3070\u9928|\u014coka Makoto Kotoba Museum]], in [[Mishima, Shizuoka|Mishima, Shizuoka Prefecture]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mitaka.jpn.org/calender/gallery/067.php|title=Makoto \u014coka Collection Exhibition|date=|publisher=Mitaka City Arts Foundation|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Motomiya began teaching printmaking techniques at the Escola Massana of Barcelona within the ''Experimental Edition Course'' of the Massana Permanent program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://robertabridda.com/?page_id=227|title=Experimental Edition Course at Massana Permanent|last=Bridda|first=Roberta|date=|website=Workshops \u2013 Massana Permanent|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> The course was taught until 2012.\n\n=== Taller Nou studio ===\nAfter settling in Barcelona, in 1989, while continuing his work in painting, he and an associate founded the Taller Nou studio, which became a printmaking studio specialized in engraving and etching techniques for professional artists.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSince the beginning of their work as printmakers, and for more than twenty years, they were the only printmaking studio of Antoni T\u00e0pies' work.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} In fact, they kept working with him until the artist's passing in 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.menorca.info/menorca/migracion/2010/02/09/514374/percepcion-desde-sentidos.html|title=Takeshi Motomiya comparte su mundo interior en Encant. Una oda de equilibrio por la esperanza.|last=Marqu\u00e9s|first=Raquel|date=February 9, 2010|work=Menorca (Newspaper)|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://botiga.fundaciotapies.org/graphic-works/vuit-i-tres-ics-2004-with-wide-margins|title=\"Vuit i tres ics\", 2004|date=|website=Antoni T\u00e0pies Foundation \u2013 Online Shop|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref> Apart from T\u00e0pies, they have worked with many other national and international artists, among which are Barry Flanagan, [[Balthus]], [[Miquel Barcel\u00f3]] and [[Perejaume]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOriginally located in the Gracia district of Barcelona, the studio has been acknowledged{{by who|date=April 2020}} as one of the best printmaking studios in Spain.<ref name=\":1\" /> Their work has been exhibited in museums around the world such as the [[Museum of Modern Art|Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)]] of New York,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/exhibitions/366|title=Antoni T\u00e0pies in Print at The Museum of Modern Art|date=May 7, 1992|website=The Museum of Modern Art (MoMA)|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref> during the ''Antoni T\u00e0pies in Print'' exhibition,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moma.org/documents/moma_press-release_327627.pdf|title=Antoni T\u00e0pies in Print Press Release|date=July 1991|access-date=January 10, 2019|publisher=MoMA (Press Release)}}</ref> or at the [[Mus\u00e9e Picasso|Mus\u00e9e Picasso Paris]], during ''Miquel Barcel\u00f3, Sol y Sombra'' exhibit in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museepicassoparis.fr/miquel-barcelo-sol-y-sombra/|title=Sol y Sombra, Miquel Barcel\u00f3 at Mus\u00e9e Picasso Paris|date=|website=Mus\u00e9e Picasso Paris|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nSelected solo and group exhibitions;<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.takeshimotomiya.com/past-exhibitions.html|title=Past Exhibitions|website=takeshimotomiya.com|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n* 1989 \u2013 Group exhibition at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain).\n* 1990 \u2013 Group exhibitions at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain), FIAC SAGA '90 (Paris, France) and Central Gallery (Sabadell, Spain).\n* 1991 \u2013 Group exhibition at Central Gallery (Sabadell, Spain).\n* 1992 \u2013 Group exhibition at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain).\n* 1993 \u2013 Group exhibition at Helena Ramos Gallery (Cadaqu\u00e9s, Spain).\n* 1996 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Artara Gallery (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 1997 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at the 5th NiCAF* (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair)(Tokyo, Japan) and Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 1998 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 1999 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan) and the 6th NiCAF* (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair)(Tokyo, Japan). Group exhibition at JADA (Japan Art Dealers Association)(Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2000 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Ueda Gallery (Tokyo, Japan) and group exhibition at JADA (Japan Art Dealers Association)(Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2001 \u2013 Solo exhibition at the 7th NiCAF* (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair)(Tokyo, Japan) and group exhibition at JADA (Japan Art Dealers Association)(Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2002 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain).\n* 2003 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2004 \u2013 Group exhibition at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain).\n* 2005 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Gallery 21 + Yo (Tokyo, Japan) and group exhibitions at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain) and Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2006 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain) and Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan). Group exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2008 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Okumura Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2009 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain) and group exhibition at Punto Arte Gallery (Barcelona, Spain).\n* 2010 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan) and group exhibition at Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n* 2011 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Galerie 421 (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2012 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Gallery Ecru-no-mori (Mishima, Japan) and Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain)\n* 2013 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan).\n* 2014 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Libre Gallery (Tokyo, Japan).\n* 2016 \u2013 Solo exhibition at Galerie Couteron (Paris, France).\n* 2017 \u2013 Solo exhibitions at Yamaguchi Gallery (Chiba, Japan), Libre Gallery (Tokyo, Japan) and Encant (Mah\u00f3n, Minorca, Spain).\n\n<small>*NICAF (Nippon International Contemporary Art Fair) \u2013 Currently known as Art Fair Tokyo.</small>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.takeshimotomiya.com Official Site]\n*[https://www.yamaguchi-gallery.com/artists/ Yamaguchi Gallery \u2013 Artist Profiles]\n*[http://www.galerie-couteron.com/artiste-takeshi_motomiya Galerie Couteron \u2013 Takeshi Motomiya] \n*[http://www.inks-passagedencres.fr/spip.php?article679 Takeshi Motomiya: M\u00e9diter, par Martine Monteau]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Motomiya, Takeshi}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese painters]]\n[[Category:Japanese contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:People from Shibuya]]\n[[Category:Tama Art University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Kirbanzo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Takeshi_Motomiya"}
{"title_page": "The Natural (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1984 film by Barry Levinson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = The Natural\n| image           = The Natural (1984 film) poster.jpg\n| image_size      = 210\n| caption         = Theatrical release poster \n| alt             = A man (Redford) standing in a field of waist high wheat, with a baseball ready to throw in one hand and a glove on the other\n| director        = [[Barry Levinson]]\n| producer        = [[Mark Johnson (producer)|Mark Johnson]]\n| screenplay      = {{ubl|Roger Towne|[[Phil Dusenberry]]}}\n| based on        = {{basedon|''[[The Natural]]''|[[Bernard Malamud]]}}\n| starring        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Redford]]\n* [[Robert Duvall]]\n* [[Glenn Close]]\n* [[Kim Basinger]]\n* [[Wilford Brimley]]\n* [[Barbara Hershey]]\n* [[Robert Prosky]]\n* [[Richard Farnsworth]]\n}}\n| music           = [[Randy Newman]]\n| cinematography  = [[Caleb Deschanel]]\n| editing         = [[Stu Linder]]\n| studio          = Delphi II Productions \n| distributor     = [[TriStar Pictures]]\n| released        = {{Film date|1984|05|11}}\n| runtime         = 138 minutes<br>144 minutes<br>(Director's Cut)\n| country         = United States\n| language        = English\n| budget          = $28 million\n| gross           = $48 million\n}}\n'''''The Natural''''' is a 1984 American [[sports film]] based on [[Bernard Malamud]]'s 1952 [[The Natural|novel of the same name]], directed by [[Barry Levinson]] and starring [[Robert Redford]], [[Glenn Close]], and [[Robert Duvall]].<ref name=sivaswrcl>{{cite journal |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1984/05/07/626594/a-star-with-real-clout |journal=Sports Illustrated |last=Fimrite |first=Ron |title=A star with real clout |date=May 7, 1984 |page=92}}</ref><ref name=sivhomyth>{{cite journal|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1984/05/21/627371/the-natural-hit-or-myth |journal=Sports Illustrated |last=Deford |first=Frank |authorlink=Frank Deford |agency=(Movies)|title=''The Natural'': hit or myth? |date=May 21, 1984 |page=71}}</ref> Like the book, the film recounts the experiences of Roy Hobbs, an individual with great \"natural\" baseball talent, spanning the decades of Roy's career. It was the first film produced by [[TriStar Pictures]].\n\nThe film was nominated for four [[57th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]], including Best Supporting Actress (Close), and it was nominated for a Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress ([[Kim Basinger]]). Many of the baseball scenes were filmed in 1983 at [[War Memorial Stadium (Buffalo)|War Memorial Stadium]] in [[Buffalo, New York]], built in 1937 and demolished in 1988. [[All-High Stadium]], also in Buffalo, stood in for [[Chicago]]'s [[Wrigley Field]] in a key scene.\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1910s Nebraska, young Roy Hobbs learns to play baseball from his father, who suffers an early fatal heart attack near an oak tree. When lightning strikes that same tree, splintering it, Hobbs makes a baseball bat from the wood, burning a lightning bolt and the name \u201cWonderboy\u201d into the barrel.\n\nNow 19 years old, Hobbs heads to Chicago for a tryout with the [[Chicago Cubs]], leaving behind his girlfriend, Iris. En route on the train, he meets legendary ballplayer the \u201cWhammer\u201d and sportswriter Max Mercy. On a stopover at a carnival, Hobbs wins a bet to strike out Whammer on three pitches. The feat catches the attention of Harriet Bird, a mysterious woman also traveling on the train who was previously fawning over Whammer.\n\nIn Chicago, Harriet invites Hobbs to her hotel room. She asks if Hobbs's claim that he can be \u201cthe best there ever was,\u201d is true, and he confidently avers it is. Harriet aims a handgun at Hobbs and shoots him in the abdomen. It is learned that Harriet, who commits suicide, previously targeted other top athletes.\n\nIn 1939, Hobbs is signed as a rookie to the New York Knights, a struggling ball club sitting in last place. Manager Pop Fisher is furious that Hobbs was recruited, believing him too old. He initially refuses to play Hobbs but finally relents. At his first batting practice, Hobbs amazes the entire team with his powerful hitting. The following game, Pop benches star outfielder Bump Bailey after a reckless play. Pop [[pinch hit]]s with Hobbs, who literally knocks the baseball's cover off. Shortly after, Bailey tragically dies crashing through an outfield wall, resulting in Hobbs being made starting outfielder. Hobbs becomes a sensation and the Knights\u2019 fortunes turn around. Mercy finds Hobbs to be familiar but fails to recognize him as the pitcher who once struck out the Whammer.\n\nAssistant manager Red Blow tells Hobbs that if Pop loses the pennant this year, then his Knight's ownership share will revert to the team's majority owner, the Judge. Pop will permanently be out of the sport. Hobbs privately meets with the Judge who offers him $5,000 to throw the season. Hobbs, unlike Bump Bailey, refuses the bribe.\n\nMercy introduces Hobbs to Gus Sands, a bookie whom Hobbs learns places large bets against him. He also meets Pop's niece, Memo Paris, who was Bump's girlfriend. Their budding relationship results in a distracted Hobbs\u2019 game slumping. Pop privately cautions Hobbs about Memo, who appears to be working for the Judge, though Hobbs dismisses his concerns.\n\nHobbs' slump continues until a game against the Cubs at [[Wrigley Field]], during which a woman in white stands up in the bleachers, catching Hobbs\u2019 attention. He then hits a home run, shattering the clock on the scoreboard. He realizes the woman is Iris, and the two later meet at a diner. They discuss their respective lives, though Hobbs avoids mentioning what happened to him. When they meet the next day, Hobbs tells Iris the truth. Iris, who is unmarried and works in [[Chicago]], shares that she has a son whose father lives in [[New York City]]. The reunion restores Hobbs' hitting prowess, and the Knights surge into first place. During a practice session, Mercy watches Hobbs pitching and suddenly remembers him.\n  \nAt a team party, Hobbs collapses in pain and awakens in a hospital. A silver bullet removed from his stomach has caused long-term damage that could prove fatal if Hobbs continues playing baseball. He learns the Knights have since lost three games in a row, which sets up a one-game playoff against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]. Memo visits Hobbs in the hospital and urges him to accept the Judge's bribe, which has been quadrupled, and to walk away. The Judge tells Hobbs to consider his offer and threatens to publicly expose Hobbs' past and reveals that another team member is being bribed. Hobbs again rejects the Judge's offer. When Iris visits Hobbs, she assures him he has not wasted his potential and is a great ballplayer.\n\nHobbs, still recovering, returns to the team wanting to play. Pop tells Hobbs that he is the best player he has ever seen and says to suit up. As the game progresses, Hobbs realizes that Knights pitcher Al Fowler is the bribed player. Hobbs confronts Fowler on the field, warning him not to throw the game. Fowler starts pitching competitively and the Knights stay in the game. Watching from the stands with her son, Iris begs an usher to deliver a note to Hobbs in the dugout, telling him that she has brought their son to watch him play.\n\nIn the ninth inning, the Knights trail the Pirates when the latter brings in a young, hard-throwing pitcher. Seeing that Hobbs is hampered by his old wound, the pitcher throws inside trying to harm him. Hobbs hits a foul but has struck the ball so hard that his bat, Wonderboy, splits in half. Hobbs asks Bobby the bat boy to pick a replacement. Bobby brings him his own bat, the \u201cSavoy Special\u201d, that Hobbs helped him make. Hobbs, down to his last strike, his wound bleeding through his jersey, hits the ball, smashing it into the stadium lights, winning the game and the National League pennant. The Knights advance to the World Series, though the outcome is not revealed. \n\nThe victory secures Pop's share of the team and his place on it. At the end, Hobbs is seen playing catch with his son in the same field that he and his father played in many years earlier, while Iris looks on.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Robert Redford]] as Roy Hobbs\n* [[Robert Duvall]] as Max Mercy\n* [[Glenn Close]] as Iris Gaines\n* [[Kim Basinger]] as Memo Paris\n* [[Wilford Brimley]] as Pop Fisher\n* [[Barbara Hershey]] as Harriet Bird\n* [[Robert Prosky]] as The Judge\n* [[Richard Farnsworth]] as Red Blow\n* [[Joe Don Baker]] as \"The Whammer\"\n* [[Darren McGavin]] as Gus Sands (uncredited)\n* [[Michael Madsen]] as Bartholomew \"Bump\" Bailey\n* [[John P. Finnegan|John Finnegan]] as Sam Simpson\n* [[Alan Fudge]] as Ed Hobbs\n* Ken Grassano as Al Fowler\n* [[Mike Starr (actor)|Mike Starr]] as Boone\n* Mickey Treanor as Doc Dizzy\n* Jon Van Ness as John Olsen\n* [[Tony Ferrara|Anthony J. Ferrara]] as Coach Wilson\n* Christopher B. Rebhaum as Pitcher John Rhoades\n* George Wilkosz as Bobby Savoy\n* Paul Sullivan Jr. as Young Roy\n* Robert Rich III as Ted Hobbs\n* Rachel Hall as Young Iris\n* [[Sibby Sisti]] as Pirates manager\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film's producers stated in the DVD extras that the film was not intended to be a literal adaptation of the novel, but was merely \"based on\" the novel. Malamud's daughter said on one of the DVD extras that her father had seen the film, and his take on it was that it had \"legitimized him as a writer.\"<ref name=\"dvd-lightning-jms\">{{cite video | people=Janna Malamud Smith (daughter of [[Bernard Malamud]]) | date=April 3, 2007 | title=When Lightning Strikes: Creating The Natural | medium=Documentary | publisher=Sony Pictures Entertainment}}</ref>\n\n[[Darren McGavin]] was cast late in the process as gambler Gus Sands and was uncredited in the film. Due to a disagreement, he chose not to be credited, though later Levinson wanted to credit him and McGavin said no.<ref name=\"dvd-lightning-bl\"/><ref>{{cite news | last=Heldenfels | first=Rich | title=Mailbag: Why do TV shows run longer than scheduled? | url=http://www.ohio.com/the330entertainment/heldenfels/mailbag-why-do-tv-shows-run-longer-than-scheduled-1.313843 | work=[[Akron Beacon-Journal]] | date=June 14, 2012 | accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref> Levinson stated on the DVD extras for the 2007 edition that because there had been too little time during post-production to find a professional announcer willing and able to provide [[voice-over]] services, Levinson recorded that part of the audio track himself.<ref name=\"dvd-lightning-bl\">{{cite video | people=[[Barry Levinson]] (director) | date=April 3, 2007 | title=When Lightning Strikes: Creating The Natural | medium=Documentary | publisher=Sony Pictures Entertainment}}</ref>\n\nTwo-thirds of the scenes were filmed in [[Buffalo, New York]], mostly at [[War Memorial Stadium (Buffalo)|War Memorial Stadium]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Film Starring Redford To Be Shot in Buffalo | work=[[The New York Times]] | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9801EFD6153BF93BA25755C0A965948260 | date=June 18, 1983 | accessdate=October 31, 2008}}</ref> built in 1937 and demolished a few years after the film was produced. Buffalo's [[All-High Stadium]], with post-production alterations, stood in for Chicago's [[Wrigley Field]] in a key scene in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/entertainment/story/305911.html|title=Wrigley Field in Buffalo|accessdate=October 5, 2008|publisher=buffalonews.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324195755/http://www.buffalonews.com/entertainment/story/305911.html|archivedate=March 24, 2008}}</ref> Additional filming took place at the [[New York and Lake Erie Railroad]] depot in [[South Dayton, New York]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chautauquatoday.com/news/details.cfm?id=92349#.WEzbL_krLIU|title=South Dayton remembers filming of|work=[[WDOE]]|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Reception===\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it an \"impeccably made ... fable about success and failure in America.\"<ref name=\"reviews\" /> [[James Berardinelli]] praised ''The Natural'' as \"[a]rguably the best baseball movie ever made\".<ref name=\"reviews\"/> [[ESPN]]'s Page 2 selected it as the 6th best sports movie of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/page2/movies/s/top20/fulllist.html|title=Page 2's Top 20 Sports Movies of All-Time|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref> Sports writer [[Bill Simmons]] has argued, \"Any 'Best Sports Movies' list that doesn't feature either ''[[Hoosiers (film)|Hoosiers]]'' or ''The Natural'' as the No. 1 pick shouldn't even count.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/page2/movies/s/simmons/020830.html|title=Holy trilogy of the 'Karate Kid'|last=Simmons|first=Bill|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDirector [[Barry Levinson]] said on [[MLB Network]]'s \"Costas at the Movies\" in 2013 that while the film is based in fantasy, \"through the years, these things which are outlandish actually [happen] ... like [[Kirk Gibson]] hitting [[1988 World Series#Game 1|the home run]] and limping around the bases ... [[Curt Schilling]] with the [[2004 American League Championship Series#Game 6|blood on the sock]] in the World Series.\"<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/video/play.jsp?content_id=25588745&topic_id=7417714 Barry Levinson, ''Costas at the Movies''], ''MLB Network'', February 11, 2013</ref>\n\n[[Leonard Maltin]]'s 18th annual ''Movie Guide'' edition called it \"too long and inconsistent.\" Dan Craft, longtime critic for the [[Bloomington, Illinois]] paper, ''The Pantagraph'',<ref>(May 19, 1984)</ref> wrote, \"The storybook ending is so preposterous you don't know whether to cheer or jeer.\" In ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'',  [[Frank Deford]] had [[Damn with faint praise|faint praise]] for it: \"''The Natural'' almost manages to be a {{nowrap|swell movie.\"<ref name=sivhomyth/>}} [[John Simon (critic)|John Simon]] of ''[[National Review]]'' and Richard Schickel of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' were disappointed with the adaptation. Simon contrasted Malamud's story about the \"failure of American innocence\" with Levinson's \"fable of success ... [and] the ultimate triumph of semi-doltish purity,\" declaring \"you have, not Malamud's novel, but a sorry illustration of its theme\".<ref>{{cite magazine | last = Simon | first = John | title = The Natural | issue = 36 | pages = 51\u20132 | magazine = [[National Review]] | date = July 13, 1984}}</ref> Schickel lamented that \"Malamud's intricate ending (it is a victory that looks like a defeat) is vulgarized (the victory is now an unambiguous triumph, fireworks included),\" and that \"watching this movie is all too often like reading about ''The Natural'' in the ''College Outline'' {{nowrap|series.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last = Schickel | first = Richard | title = The Natural | volume= | issue = 123 | page = 91 | language = | journal = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date = May 14, 1984}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] called it \"idolatry on behalf of Robert Redford.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite web | last = Ebert | first = Roger | authorlink = Roger Ebert | title = The Natural | work = | publisher = rogerebert.com | date = January 1, 1984 | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19840101/REVIEWS/401010363/1023 | doi = | accessdate = January 10, 2008}}</ref> Ebert's television collaborator [[Gene Siskel]] praised it, giving it four stars, also putting down other critics that he suggested might have just recently read the novel for the {{nowrap|first time.<ref>{{cite news | last = Siskel | first = Gene | title = 'The Natural': Redford scores in an uplifting celebration of the individual | pages = D A1 | newspaper = Chicago Tribune | date = May 11, 1984 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn a lengthy article on baseball movies in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', [[Roger Angell]] pointed out that Malamud had intentionally treated Hobbs' story as a baseball version of the [[King Arthur]] legend, which came across in the film as a bit heavy-handed, \"portentous and stuffy,\" and that the book's ending should have been kept. He also cited a number of excellent visuals and funny bits, and noted that Robert Redford had prepared so carefully for the role, modeling his swing on that of [[Ted Williams]], that \"you want to sign {{nowrap|him up.\"<ref>{{cite journal|first=Roger|last=Angell|title=No, But I Saw The Game|journal=The New Yorker|date=July 31, 1989|page=41}}</ref>}}\n\nAt the film [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], retrospectively compiled reviews from 39 critics give the film a score of 82%, with an average rating of 7.1/10. The website's consensus reads: \"Though heavy with sentiment, ''The Natural'' is an irresistible classic, and a sincere testament to America's {{nowrap|national pastime.\"<ref name=\"reviews\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/natural/ |title=The Natural (1984) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n===Awards and honors===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\n''The Natural'' was nominated for four [[57th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]: Actress in a Supporting Role ([[Glenn Close]]), Cinematography ([[Caleb Deschanel]]), Art Direction ([[Mel Bourne]], [[Angelo P. Graham]], [[Bruce Weintraub]]), and Music ([[Randy Newman]]).<ref>{{cite web| title =Academy Awards Database: The Natural (57th-1984)| publisher =[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]| url =http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1200879955474| archive-url =https://archive.is/20120711154212/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1200879955474| url-status =dead| archive-date =July 11, 2012| accessdate =January 20, 2008}}</ref> [[Kim Basinger]] was also nominated for Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/34607/The-Natural/awards |title=NY Times: The Natural |accessdate=January 1, 2009|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n==Home video==\n{{Anchor|DVD|Home media}}\nThe initial DVD edition, with copyright year on the box reading \"2001\", contained the theatrical version of the film, along with a few specials and commentaries.\n\nThe \"director's cut\" was released on April 3, 2007.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics1\">{{cite web| title =DVD - The Natural (Director's Cut)| publisher =Monsters and Critics.com, WotR Ltd.| url =http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/archive/dvdarchive.php/The_Natural_%28Director%27s_Cut%29/10359| archive-url =https://archive.is/20130129034150/http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/archive/dvdarchive.php/The_Natural_(Director's_Cut)/10359| url-status =dead| archive-date =January 29, 2013| accessdate =January 20, 2008}}</ref> A two-disc edition, it contains the featurette \"The Heart of the Natural,\" a 44-minute documentary featuring comments from [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]] and Levinson; it is the only extra released originally with the 2001 DVD. Sony added a number of other extras, however, including: \"When Lightning Strikes: Creating ''The Natural'',\" a 50-minute documentary discussing the origins of the original novel and the production of the film; \"Knights in Shining Armor,\" which addresses the mythological parallels between ''The Natural'', King Arthur and the ''[[Odyssey]]''; and \"A Natural Gunned Down\" which tells the story of [[Eddie Waitkus]], a baseball player who was shot by [[Ruth Ann Steinhagen]], a female stalker, in an incident which inspired the fictionalized shooting of Roy Hobbs.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics2\">{{cite web | last = Tezer | first = Adnan | title = DVD Review: The Natural (Director\u2019s Cut) | publisher = Monsters and Critics.com, WotR Ltd. | date = April 1, 2007 | url = http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/reviews/article_1285572.php | accessdate = January 20, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080121153131/http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/reviews/article_1285572.php | archivedate = January 21, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  The film itself has been re-edited, restoring deleted footage to the early chapters of the story. These scenes expand on the sadness of Hobbs, focusing on his visits to his childhood home as an adult and his childhood memories.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics2\" />\nThe \"gift set\" version of the release also included some souvenirs: a baseball \"signed\" by Roy Hobbs; some baseball cards of Roy Hobbs and teammates; and a New York Knights cap.\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe [[film score]] of ''The Natural'' was composed and conducted by [[Randy Newman]].<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | title = The Natural (1984 Film) [SOUNDTRACK]  | work = | publisher = [[Amazon.com]] | url = https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000002L6A | doi = | accessdate = January 20, 2008}}</ref> The score has often been compared to the style of [[Aaron Copland]] and sometimes [[Elmer Bernstein]]. Scott Montgomery, writing for ''[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]]'' music magazine, referenced the influence, and [[David Ansen]], reviewing the film for ''[[Newsweek]]'', called the score \"Coplandesque.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Montgomery |first=Scott |author2=Gary Norris |author3=Kevin Walsh |title=The Invisible Randy Newman |volume=21 |issue=18 |magazine=[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]] |date=September 1, 1995 |url=http://www.randynewman.info/biography/a10.html |accessdate=January 20, 2008 |quote=''The Natural'', a 1984 Robert Redford vehicle based on the classic Bernard Malamud novel about a baseball player, features some of Newman's most inspiring movie music \u2014 his first score to feature synthesizers prominently in string arrangements. Leaning gently on Copland, Berlin and his uncle Al, the dramatic title theme (which has been heard in virtually every baseball-related film trailer since the movie's release) earned Newman both an Academy Award nomination for best soundtrack and a 1985 Grammy Award for Best Instrumental. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817154932/http://www.randynewman.info/biography/a10.html |archivedate=August 17, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| last = Ansen | first = David | authorlink = David Ansen | title = The Natural | magazine = [[Newsweek]] | date = May 28, 1984 }}</ref>  The score also has certain Wagnerian features of orchestration and use of Leitmotif. Adnan Tezer of ''Monsters and Critics'' noted the theme is often played for film and television previews and in \"baseball stadiums when introducing home teams and players.\"<ref name=\"monstersandcritics2\" />\n\nLevinson also described to [[Bob Costas]] in [[MLB Network]]'s \"Costas at the Movies\" how he heard Newman develop the movie's iconic theme: \"We were racing to try to get this movie out in time and we were in one room and then there was a wall and Randy's in the other room. One of the great thrilling moments is I heard him figuring out that theme...You could hear it through the wall as he was working out that theme and I'll never forget that.\"\n\nThe soundtrack album was released May 11<!--, 1984,--> on the [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] label, with the logo for Tri-Star Pictures also appearing on the label to commemorate this as their first production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/release/2898649-The-Natural/images|title=Images for Randy Newman - The Natural|website=www.discogs.com}}</ref><!-- All music was composed by Newman.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | title = The Natural (1984 Film) [SOUNDTRACK]  | work = | publisher = [[Amazon.com]] | url = https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000002L6A | doi = | accessdate = January 20, 2008}}</ref>-->\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Baseball|Film|United States}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0087781|title=The Natural}}\n* {{mojo title|id=natural|title=The Natural}}\n\n{{Barry Levinson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Natural, The}}\n[[Category:1984 films]]\n[[Category:1980s sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American sports drama films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Barry Levinson]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Randy Newman]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1910s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1923]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1939]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1984 film by Barry Levinson}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name            = The Natural\n| image           = The Natural (1984 film) poster.jpg\n| image_size      = 210\n| caption         = Theatrical release poster \n| alt             = A man (Redford) standing in a field of waist high wheat, with a baseball ready to throw in one hand and a glove on the other\n| director        = [[Barry Levinson]]\n| producer        = [[Mark Johnson (producer)|Mark Johnson]]\n| screenplay      = {{ubl|Roger Towne|[[Phil Dusenberry]]}}\n| based on        = {{basedon|''[[The Natural]]''|[[Bernard Malamud]]}}\n| starring        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Redford]]\n* [[Robert Duvall]]\n* [[Glenn Close]]\n* [[Kim Basinger]]\n* [[Wilford Brimley]]\n* [[Barbara Hershey]]\n* [[Robert Prosky]]\n* [[Richard Farnsworth]]\n}}\n| music           = [[Randy Newman]]\n| cinematography  = [[Caleb Deschanel]]\n| editing         = [[Stu Linder]]\n| studio          = Delphi II Productions \n| distributor     = [[TriStar Pictures]]\n| released        = {{Film date|1984|05|11}}\n| runtime         = 138 minutes<br>144 minutes<br>(Director's Cut)\n| country         = United States\n| language        = English\n| budget          = $28 million\n| gross           = $48 million\n}}\n'''''The Natural''''' is a 1984 American [[sports film]] based on [[Bernard Malamud]]'s 1952 [[The Natural|novel of the same name]], directed by [[Barry Levinson]] and starring [[Robert Redford]], [[Glenn Close]], and [[Robert Duvall]].<ref name=sivaswrcl>{{cite journal |url=https://www.si.com/vault/1984/05/07/626594/a-star-with-real-clout |journal=Sports Illustrated |last=Fimrite |first=Ron |title=A star with real clout |date=May 7, 1984 |page=92}}</ref><ref name=sivhomyth>{{cite journal|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1984/05/21/627371/the-natural-hit-or-myth |journal=Sports Illustrated |last=Deford |first=Frank |authorlink=Frank Deford |agency=(Movies)|title=''The Natural'': hit or myth? |date=May 21, 1984 |page=71}}</ref> Like the book, the film recounts the experiences of Roy Hobbs, an individual with great \"natural\" baseball talent, spanning the decades of Roy's career. It was the first film produced by [[TriStar Pictures]].\n\nThe film was nominated for four [[57th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]], including Best Supporting Actress (Close), and it was nominated for a Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress ([[Kim Basinger]]). Many of the baseball scenes were filmed in 1983 at [[War Memorial Stadium (Buffalo)|War Memorial Stadium]] in [[Buffalo, New York]], built in 1937 and demolished in 1988. [[All-High Stadium]], also in Buffalo, stood in for [[Chicago]]'s [[Wrigley Field]] in a key scene.\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1910s Nebraska, young Roy Hobbs learns to play baseball from his father, who suffers an early fatal heart attack near an oak tree. When lightning strikes that same tree, splintering it, Hobbs makes a baseball bat from the wood, burning a lightning bolt and the name \u201cWonderboy\u201d into the barrel.\n\nNow 19 years old, Hobbs heads to Chicago for a tryout with the [[Chicago Cubs]], leaving behind his girlfriend, Iris. En route on the train, he meets legendary ballplayer the \u201cWhammer\u201d and sportswriter Max Mercy. On a stopover at a carnival, Hobbs wins a bet to strike out Whammer on three pitches. The feat catches the attention of Harriet Bird, a mysterious woman also traveling on the train who was previously fawning over Whammer.\n\nIn Chicago, Harriet invites Hobbs to her hotel room. She asks if Hobbs's claim that he can be \u201cthe best there ever was,\u201d is true, and he confidently avers it is. Harriet aims a handgun at Hobbs and shoots him in the abdomen. It is learned that Harriet, who commits suicide, previously targeted other top athletes.\n\nIn 1939, Hobbs is signed as a rookie to the New York Knights, a struggling ball club sitting in last place. Manager Pop Fisher is furious that Hobbs was recruited, believing him too old. He initially refuses to play Hobbs but finally relents. At his first batting practice, Hobbs amazes the entire team with his powerful hitting. The following game, Pop benches star outfielder Bump Bailey after a reckless play. Pop [[pinch hit]]s with Hobbs, who literally knocks the baseball's cover off. Shortly after, Bailey tragically dies crashing through an outfield wall, resulting in Hobbs being made starting outfielder. Hobbs becomes a sensation and the Knights\u2019 fortunes turn around. Mercy finds Hobbs to be familiar but fails to recognize him as the pitcher who once struck out the Whammer.\n\nAssistant manager Red Blow tells Hobbs that if Pop loses the pennant this year, then his Knight's ownership share will revert to the team's majority owner, the Judge. Pop will permanently be out of the sport. Hobbs privately meets with the Judge who offers him $5,000 to throw the season. Hobbs, unlike Bump Bailey, refuses the bribe.\n\nMercy introduces Hobbs to Gus Sands, a bookie whom Hobbs learns places large bets against him. He also meets Pop's niece, Memo Paris, who was Bump's girlfriend. Their budding relationship results in a distracted Hobbs\u2019 game slumping. Pop privately cautions Hobbs about Memo, who appears to be working for the Judge, though Hobbs dismisses his concerns.\n\nHobbs' slump continues until a game against the Cubs at [[Wrigley Field]], during which a woman in white stands up in the bleachers, catching Hobbs\u2019 attention. He then hits a home run, shattering the clock on the scoreboard. He realizes the woman is Iris, and the two later meet at a diner. They discuss their respective lives, though Hobbs avoids mentioning what happened to him. When they meet the next day, Hobbs tells Iris the truth. Iris, who is unmarried and works in [[Chicago]], shares that she has a son whose father lives in [[New York City]]. The reunion restores Hobbs' hitting prowess, and the Knights surge into first place. During a practice session, Mercy watches Hobbs pitching and suddenly remembers him.\n  \nAt a team party, Hobbs collapses in pain and awakens in a hospital. A silver bullet removed from his stomach has caused long-term damage that could prove fatal if Hobbs continues playing baseball. He learns the Knights have since lost three games in a row, which sets up a one-game playoff against the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]]. Memo visits Hobbs in the hospital and urges him to accept the Judge's bribe, which has been quadrupled, and to walk away. The Judge tells Hobbs to consider his offer and threatens to publicly expose Hobbs' past and reveals that another team member is being bribed. Hobbs again rejects the Judge's offer. When Iris visits Hobbs, she assures him he has not wasted his potential and is a great ballplayer.\n\nHobbs, still recovering, returns to the team wanting to play. Pop tells Hobbs that he is the best player he has ever seen and says to suit up. As the game progresses, Hobbs realizes that Knights pitcher Al Fowler is the bribed player. Hobbs confronts Fowler on the field, warning him not to throw the game. Fowler starts pitching competitively and the Knights stay in the game. Watching from the stands with her son, Iris begs an usher to deliver a note to Hobbs in the dugout, telling him that she has brought their son to watch him play.\n\nIn the ninth inning, the Knights trail the Pirates when the latter brings in a young, hard-throwing pitcher. Seeing that Hobbs is hampered by his old wound, the pitcher throws inside trying to harm him. Hobbs hits a foul but has struck the ball so hard that his bat, Wonderboy, splits in half. Hobbs asks Bobby the bat boy to pick a replacement. Bobby brings him his own bat, the \u201cSavoy Special\u201d, that Hobbs helped him make. Hobbs, down to his last strike, his wound bleeding through his jersey, hits the ball, smashing it into the stadium lights, winning the game and the National League pennant. The Knights advance to the World Series, though the outcome is not revealed. \n\nThe victory secures Pop's share of the team and his place on it. At the end, Hobbs is seen playing catch with his son in the same field that he and his father played in many years earlier, while Iris looks on.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[Robert Redford]] as Roy Hobbs\n* [[Robert Duvall]] as Max Mercy\n* [[Glenn Close]] as Iris Gaines\n* [[Kim Basinger]] as Memo Paris\n* [[Wilford Brimley]] as Pop Fisher\n* [[Barbara Hershey]] as Harriet Bird\n* [[Robert Prosky]] as The Judge\n* [[Richard Farnsworth]] as Red Blow\n* [[Joe Don Baker]] as \"The Whammer\"\n* [[Darren McGavin]] as Gus Sands (uncredited)\n* [[Michael Madsen]] as Bartholomew \"Bump\" Bailey\n* [[John P. Finnegan|John Finnegan]] as Sam Simpson\n* [[Alan Fudge]] as Ed Hobbs\n* Ken Grassano as Al Fowler\n* [[Mike Starr (actor)|Mike Starr]] as Boone\n* Mickey Treanor as Doc Dizzy\n* Jon Van Ness as John Olsen\n* [[Tony Ferrara|Anthony J. Ferrara]] as Coach Wilson\n* George Wilkosz as Bobby Savoy\n* Paul Sullivan Jr. as Young Roy\n* Robert Rich III as Ted Hobbs\n* Rachel Hall as Young Iris\n* [[Sibby Sisti]] as Pirates manager\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nThe film's producers stated in the DVD extras that the film was not intended to be a literal adaptation of the novel, but was merely \"based on\" the novel. Malamud's daughter said on one of the DVD extras that her father had seen the film, and his take on it was that it had \"legitimized him as a writer.\"<ref name=\"dvd-lightning-jms\">{{cite video | people=Janna Malamud Smith (daughter of [[Bernard Malamud]]) | date=April 3, 2007 | title=When Lightning Strikes: Creating The Natural | medium=Documentary | publisher=Sony Pictures Entertainment}}</ref>\n\n[[Darren McGavin]] was cast late in the process as gambler Gus Sands and was uncredited in the film. Due to a disagreement, he chose not to be credited, though later Levinson wanted to credit him and McGavin said no.<ref name=\"dvd-lightning-bl\"/><ref>{{cite news | last=Heldenfels | first=Rich | title=Mailbag: Why do TV shows run longer than scheduled? | url=http://www.ohio.com/the330entertainment/heldenfels/mailbag-why-do-tv-shows-run-longer-than-scheduled-1.313843 | work=[[Akron Beacon-Journal]] | date=June 14, 2012 | accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref> Levinson stated on the DVD extras for the 2007 edition that because there had been too little time during post-production to find a professional announcer willing and able to provide [[voice-over]] services, Levinson recorded that part of the audio track himself.<ref name=\"dvd-lightning-bl\">{{cite video | people=[[Barry Levinson]] (director) | date=April 3, 2007 | title=When Lightning Strikes: Creating The Natural | medium=Documentary | publisher=Sony Pictures Entertainment}}</ref>\n\nTwo-thirds of the scenes were filmed in [[Buffalo, New York]], mostly at [[War Memorial Stadium (Buffalo)|War Memorial Stadium]],<ref>{{cite news | title=Film Starring Redford To Be Shot in Buffalo | work=[[The New York Times]] | url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9801EFD6153BF93BA25755C0A965948260 | date=June 18, 1983 | accessdate=October 31, 2008}}</ref> built in 1937 and demolished a few years after the film was produced. Buffalo's [[All-High Stadium]], with post-production alterations, stood in for Chicago's [[Wrigley Field]] in a key scene in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffalonews.com/entertainment/story/305911.html|title=Wrigley Field in Buffalo|accessdate=October 5, 2008|publisher=buffalonews.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080324195755/http://www.buffalonews.com/entertainment/story/305911.html|archivedate=March 24, 2008}}</ref> Additional filming took place at the [[New York and Lake Erie Railroad]] depot in [[South Dayton, New York]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chautauquatoday.com/news/details.cfm?id=92349#.WEzbL_krLIU|title=South Dayton remembers filming of|work=[[WDOE]]|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\n===Reception===\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it an \"impeccably made ... fable about success and failure in America.\"<ref name=\"reviews\" /> [[James Berardinelli]] praised ''The Natural'' as \"[a]rguably the best baseball movie ever made\".<ref name=\"reviews\"/> [[ESPN]]'s Page 2 selected it as the 6th best sports movie of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/page2/movies/s/top20/fulllist.html|title=Page 2's Top 20 Sports Movies of All-Time|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref> Sports writer [[Bill Simmons]] has argued, \"Any 'Best Sports Movies' list that doesn't feature either ''[[Hoosiers (film)|Hoosiers]]'' or ''The Natural'' as the No. 1 pick shouldn't even count.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/page2/movies/s/simmons/020830.html|title=Holy trilogy of the 'Karate Kid'|last=Simmons|first=Bill|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 12, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDirector [[Barry Levinson]] said on [[MLB Network]]'s \"Costas at the Movies\" in 2013 that while the film is based in fantasy, \"through the years, these things which are outlandish actually [happen] ... like [[Kirk Gibson]] hitting [[1988 World Series#Game 1|the home run]] and limping around the bases ... [[Curt Schilling]] with the [[2004 American League Championship Series#Game 6|blood on the sock]] in the World Series.\"<ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/video/play.jsp?content_id=25588745&topic_id=7417714 Barry Levinson, ''Costas at the Movies''], ''MLB Network'', February 11, 2013</ref>\n\n[[Leonard Maltin]]'s 18th annual ''Movie Guide'' edition called it \"too long and inconsistent.\" Dan Craft, longtime critic for the [[Bloomington, Illinois]] paper, ''The Pantagraph'',<ref>(May 19, 1984)</ref> wrote, \"The storybook ending is so preposterous you don't know whether to cheer or jeer.\" In ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'',  [[Frank Deford]] had [[Damn with faint praise|faint praise]] for it: \"''The Natural'' almost manages to be a {{nowrap|swell movie.\"<ref name=sivhomyth/>}} [[John Simon (critic)|John Simon]] of ''[[National Review]]'' and Richard Schickel of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' were disappointed with the adaptation. Simon contrasted Malamud's story about the \"failure of American innocence\" with Levinson's \"fable of success ... [and] the ultimate triumph of semi-doltish purity,\" declaring \"you have, not Malamud's novel, but a sorry illustration of its theme\".<ref>{{cite magazine | last = Simon | first = John | title = The Natural | issue = 36 | pages = 51\u20132 | magazine = [[National Review]] | date = July 13, 1984}}</ref> Schickel lamented that \"Malamud's intricate ending (it is a victory that looks like a defeat) is vulgarized (the victory is now an unambiguous triumph, fireworks included),\" and that \"watching this movie is all too often like reading about ''The Natural'' in the ''College Outline'' {{nowrap|series.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last = Schickel | first = Richard | title = The Natural | volume= | issue = 123 | page = 91 | language = | journal = [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | date = May 14, 1984}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] called it \"idolatry on behalf of Robert Redford.\"<ref name=\"ebert\">{{cite web | last = Ebert | first = Roger | authorlink = Roger Ebert | title = The Natural | work = | publisher = rogerebert.com | date = January 1, 1984 | url = http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19840101/REVIEWS/401010363/1023 | doi = | accessdate = January 10, 2008}}</ref> Ebert's television collaborator [[Gene Siskel]] praised it, giving it four stars, also putting down other critics that he suggested might have just recently read the novel for the {{nowrap|first time.<ref>{{cite news | last = Siskel | first = Gene | title = 'The Natural': Redford scores in an uplifting celebration of the individual | pages = D A1 | newspaper = Chicago Tribune | date = May 11, 1984 }}</ref>}}\n\nIn a lengthy article on baseball movies in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', [[Roger Angell]] pointed out that Malamud had intentionally treated Hobbs' story as a baseball version of the [[King Arthur]] legend, which came across in the film as a bit heavy-handed, \"portentous and stuffy,\" and that the book's ending should have been kept. He also cited a number of excellent visuals and funny bits, and noted that Robert Redford had prepared so carefully for the role, modeling his swing on that of [[Ted Williams]], that \"you want to sign {{nowrap|him up.\"<ref>{{cite journal|first=Roger|last=Angell|title=No, But I Saw The Game|journal=The New Yorker|date=July 31, 1989|page=41}}</ref>}}\n\nAt the film [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], retrospectively compiled reviews from 39 critics give the film a score of 82%, with an average rating of 7.1/10. The website's consensus reads: \"Though heavy with sentiment, ''The Natural'' is an irresistible classic, and a sincere testament to America's {{nowrap|national pastime.\"<ref name=\"reviews\">{{cite web |url= http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/natural/ |title=The Natural (1984) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=April 3, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\n===Awards and honors===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\n''The Natural'' was nominated for four [[57th Academy Awards|Academy Awards]]: Actress in a Supporting Role ([[Glenn Close]]), Cinematography ([[Caleb Deschanel]]), Art Direction ([[Mel Bourne]], [[Angelo P. Graham]], [[Bruce Weintraub]]), and Music ([[Randy Newman]]).<ref>{{cite web| title =Academy Awards Database: The Natural (57th-1984)| publisher =[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]| url =http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1200879955474| archive-url =https://archive.is/20120711154212/http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp?curTime=1200879955474| url-status =dead| archive-date =July 11, 2012| accessdate =January 20, 2008}}</ref> [[Kim Basinger]] was also nominated for Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/34607/The-Natural/awards |title=NY Times: The Natural |accessdate=January 1, 2009|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n==Home video==\n{{Anchor|DVD|Home media}}\nThe initial DVD edition, with copyright year on the box reading \"2001\", contained the theatrical version of the film, along with a few specials and commentaries.\n\nThe \"director's cut\" was released on April 3, 2007.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics1\">{{cite web| title =DVD - The Natural (Director's Cut)| publisher =Monsters and Critics.com, WotR Ltd.| url =http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/archive/dvdarchive.php/The_Natural_%28Director%27s_Cut%29/10359| archive-url =https://archive.is/20130129034150/http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/archive/dvdarchive.php/The_Natural_(Director's_Cut)/10359| url-status =dead| archive-date =January 29, 2013| accessdate =January 20, 2008}}</ref> A two-disc edition, it contains the featurette \"The Heart of the Natural,\" a 44-minute documentary featuring comments from [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]] and Levinson; it is the only extra released originally with the 2001 DVD. Sony added a number of other extras, however, including: \"When Lightning Strikes: Creating ''The Natural'',\" a 50-minute documentary discussing the origins of the original novel and the production of the film; \"Knights in Shining Armor,\" which addresses the mythological parallels between ''The Natural'', King Arthur and the ''[[Odyssey]]''; and \"A Natural Gunned Down\" which tells the story of [[Eddie Waitkus]], a baseball player who was shot by [[Ruth Ann Steinhagen]], a female stalker, in an incident which inspired the fictionalized shooting of Roy Hobbs.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics2\">{{cite web | last = Tezer | first = Adnan | title = DVD Review: The Natural (Director\u2019s Cut) | publisher = Monsters and Critics.com, WotR Ltd. | date = April 1, 2007 | url = http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/reviews/article_1285572.php | accessdate = January 20, 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080121153131/http://dvd.monstersandcritics.com/reviews/article_1285572.php | archivedate = January 21, 2008 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>  The film itself has been re-edited, restoring deleted footage to the early chapters of the story. These scenes expand on the sadness of Hobbs, focusing on his visits to his childhood home as an adult and his childhood memories.<ref name=\"monstersandcritics2\" />\nThe \"gift set\" version of the release also included some souvenirs: a baseball \"signed\" by Roy Hobbs; some baseball cards of Roy Hobbs and teammates; and a New York Knights cap.\n\n==Soundtrack==\nThe [[film score]] of ''The Natural'' was composed and conducted by [[Randy Newman]].<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | title = The Natural (1984 Film) [SOUNDTRACK]  | work = | publisher = [[Amazon.com]] | url = https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000002L6A | doi = | accessdate = January 20, 2008}}</ref> The score has often been compared to the style of [[Aaron Copland]] and sometimes [[Elmer Bernstein]]. Scott Montgomery, writing for ''[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]]'' music magazine, referenced the influence, and [[David Ansen]], reviewing the film for ''[[Newsweek]]'', called the score \"Coplandesque.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Montgomery |first=Scott |author2=Gary Norris |author3=Kevin Walsh |title=The Invisible Randy Newman |volume=21 |issue=18 |magazine=[[Goldmine (magazine)|Goldmine]] |date=September 1, 1995 |url=http://www.randynewman.info/biography/a10.html |accessdate=January 20, 2008 |quote=''The Natural'', a 1984 Robert Redford vehicle based on the classic Bernard Malamud novel about a baseball player, features some of Newman's most inspiring movie music \u2014 his first score to feature synthesizers prominently in string arrangements. Leaning gently on Copland, Berlin and his uncle Al, the dramatic title theme (which has been heard in virtually every baseball-related film trailer since the movie's release) earned Newman both an Academy Award nomination for best soundtrack and a 1985 Grammy Award for Best Instrumental. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070817154932/http://www.randynewman.info/biography/a10.html |archivedate=August 17, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| last = Ansen | first = David | authorlink = David Ansen | title = The Natural | magazine = [[Newsweek]] | date = May 28, 1984 }}</ref>  The score also has certain Wagnerian features of orchestration and use of Leitmotif. Adnan Tezer of ''Monsters and Critics'' noted the theme is often played for film and television previews and in \"baseball stadiums when introducing home teams and players.\"<ref name=\"monstersandcritics2\" />\n\nLevinson also described to [[Bob Costas]] in [[MLB Network]]'s \"Costas at the Movies\" how he heard Newman develop the movie's iconic theme: \"We were racing to try to get this movie out in time and we were in one room and then there was a wall and Randy's in the other room. One of the great thrilling moments is I heard him figuring out that theme...You could hear it through the wall as he was working out that theme and I'll never forget that.\"\n\nThe soundtrack album was released May 11<!--, 1984,--> on the [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] label, with the logo for Tri-Star Pictures also appearing on the label to commemorate this as their first production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/release/2898649-The-Natural/images|title=Images for Randy Newman - The Natural|website=www.discogs.com}}</ref><!-- All music was composed by Newman.<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | title = The Natural (1984 Film) [SOUNDTRACK]  | work = | publisher = [[Amazon.com]] | url = https://www.amazon.com/dp/B000002L6A | doi = | accessdate = January 20, 2008}}</ref>-->\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal bar|Baseball|Film|United States}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0087781|title=The Natural}}\n* {{mojo title|id=natural|title=The Natural}}\n\n{{Barry Levinson}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Natural, The}}\n[[Category:1984 films]]\n[[Category:1980s sports drama films]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American sports drama films]]\n[[Category:Films based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Barry Levinson]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Randy Newman]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1910s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1923]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1939]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:TriStar Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "2601:18d:8d7f:dbc0:b040:7047:497d:1348", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCast:Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Natural_(film)"}
